node.text:
Proper core and pelvic core control is not just for my baby mamas :) This proper activation and breathing technique is something everyone should be able to do. 

A diastasis recti can happen to anyone, not just pregnant woman. I have treated male patients for this issue as well! You can also see this midline bulge with people who are unable to regulate their core properly during certain exercises. So being able to control that outward pressure that causes your belly to bulge is an important skill to have for everyone!

Some benefits of these exercises techniques:
👉🏼prevention and treatment of a diastasis recti
👉🏼prevention and treatment of urinary incontinence or other pelvic floor related issues
👉🏼help regulate intra-abdominal pressure and overall core control
👉🏼appropriate for pre/postnatal women

This is what you see me doing in my workout videos. Being able to breathe through exercises and engage properly will continue to be super important as I go though my pregnancy! 

#daretobeactiveprepostnatal

node.text:
So I don’t talk about personal things very often, but I wouldn’t feel right starting to post again about exercise and pregnancy without sharing my journey thus far. It has been a long tough road, and I know hearing other women’s stories helped me. So maybe sharing a little bit of mine could help someone else. 

I should note that I got in a bad habit of calling Hyperemesis gravidarum the wrong thing and I kept doing it in this video 🤦🏻‍♀️ So apologies for that.

To all the women who went through or are going through HG or fertility problems...I feel you. You are a badass. You got this. 

#hyperemisisgravidarum #infertility

node.title: Pregnancy Journey + my experience with HG

node.text:
Everyone needs to be training their rotator cuff muscles. Why? Watch the video to learn. 

These muscles are dynamic stabilizers, so aim for high repetition with low weight. Three sets to failure is a good place to start. Failure means you are unable to compete the full range of motion or you lose correct form.

More exercises to follow!

#daretobeactiveshoulders
#daretobeactiveupperbody 
#daretobeactive

node.text:
🤱🏻The early postpartum days are all about rest and recovery for your body. You just spent 9 months growing a human, giving birth, and now are in the wrath of 4th trimester of little sleep and likely breastfeeding woes for those who chose to BF. 

✋🏽Working on your core at this time is not about getting your body back. It’s about reteaching your core and pelvic floor muscles how to work together to give you support and stability. You can start to do this immediately postpartum with gentle breath to core connection. 

👉🏼Here are some different positions you can start to work on this. Do whatever works for you! My favorite place to work on this was just laying in bed, and believe me, it doesn’t feel like much is happening at first 🙃 

🌬Doing light mobility and deep core and breath connection will help build the foundation to prepare you to get back to gradual exercise if you get cleared at the typical 6 week mark.

If you notice, this is the same breath and core work you do throughout pregnancy 😉

If you are having any pain or need more guidance please check with your care provider or see a pelvic health physical therapist!

#daretobeactiveprepostnatal

node.text: Was going to post these on national dog day but here we are. Jett and Nora were pretty indifferent lol but here is Rookie staying by my side as I labored at home for 12 hours, helping G coach and support me physically and mentally through the most painful back stabbing contractions, all the way through packing last minute things to head to the hospital. She is definitely a little sad that I have a new side kick but I am so glad G took these to remember how much she stayed by my side 😢 We made it to the hospital with Juni fully ready to make her appearance. Hopped in the tub for comfort and decided to stay there to have her, and she came an hour and a half later :) It was extremely painful lol but one of the most amazing and emotional experiences I have ever had. So thankful for my hubs and Rookie and my amazing midwives and nurses 🤍 I am still in awe of what women’s bodies can endure!

node.text:
👉🏼LABOR PREP —— Pelvic movements and asymmetrical exercises meant to engage baby in the pelvis. Again I went into labor the next night after doing these and the workout in my previous reel. I feel like it goes without saying but I should say it anyways — doing these does not mean you will go into labor. But if your body is ready, it can help get that baby in the right position! 

👍🏼 These are great to do throughout your pregnancy as well. They can help manage back and pelvic pain and help open your hips and pelvic girdle.

- Pelvic tilts - anterior/posterior, lateral, circles both directions
- Lateral shifts 
- Wide stance thoracic rotation (this can be done with elbows on knees if reaching the floor is  difficult) this is one of my favs! 
- Figure 4 stretch 
- Half kneel rocking

🤰🏻Happy labor prep mamas! 

#daretobeactiveprepostnatal

node.text:
LABOR PREP — My last workout before Juniper arrived! Went into labor the next night 😅 These exercises plus the Swissball stretches I’ll also post are types of moves meant to engage the baby in the pelvis.

I did 4 sets of 10 and also went on a mile walk 🚶🏻‍♀️

#daretobeactiveprepostnatal

node.text: Juniper Grace Louise is here and mama and papa are absolutely obsessed 🤍 We will be very busy kissing and sniffing every inch of her until she is old enough to tell us it’s weird 😏
